from website:
Marcus Duron is President & CEO of Rocky Duron & Associates ("RDA"), a family owned company that has been in business for 27 years. The company was started in the back of his father's garage, and today is one of the M/WBE leading material handling companies in the US, having been ranked in the US Hispanic Business Magazine Top 500 Hispanic-Owned businesses in the US the past 10 years. Additionally, RDA was the recent recipient of the Greater Dallas Hispanic Chamber of Commerce Company of the Year Award recently.  Amongst notable projects his company just successfully completed was the George W. Bush Presidential Library at his alma mater as he just recently attended the Grand Opening of the Bush Library Thursday May  2, 2013.

Marcus, graduated from Southern Methodist University with degrees in Psychology and Communications. While there, he was President of the College Hispanic Student Organization.  Upon graduation, Marcus moved to New York City, where he worked in the international sales division of Dow Jones/The Wall Street Journal, where he traveled extensively throughout Europe and Asia. He then decided to run for the New York State Assembly, representing the residents of the Upper East Side of Manhattan. Though he received the endorsements of Mayor Rudy Giuliani and US Senator Alphonse D'Amato, he was unsuccessful in his run for office, yet was appointed by Governor George Pataki as one of the Director's for the New York Department  of Economic Development.

Marcus has been on the SMU Alumni Board of Directors for the past four years. He has served as Chairman of the Campus Outreach Committee and Chairman of the Annual SMU Distinguished Alumni Awards Gala.  He is also on the Lee Park Arlington Hall Conservancy Board of Directors, which is Dallas' oldest park located in Turtle Creek and was on the Board of Directors for the Greater Dallas Hispanic Chamber of Commerce. 

His hobbies include tennis, as he played in college and made All State in High School, an avid golfer as he just recently played golf in Ireland and Pebble Beach and loves to travel abroad, especially to Europe.  He is the fourth born of five kids; his parents just recently had their 55th wedding anniversary.  His parents both graduated from DISD schools and father did not learn English until he was 15. Yet all five of their kids graduated from college.  Marcus is a single, and proud father of his young daughter Sophia, who lives in NYC.

A native of Fresno, California, Stephanie made the move to Austin to join studioSIX5. She has 10 years’ experience in interior design and project management. She believes the most important part of being an interior designer is maintaining constant contact and open communication with the client. Her favorite studioSIX5 projects are Cottonwood Place in Holladay, Utah, The Village at Stonebridge in McKinney, Texas, Eden Hill in New Braunfels, Texas, and Vivante on the Coast in Costa Mesa, California.

Stephanie is passionate about cooking, family and traveling. Her hobby is doing anything outdoors with her family. She loves country music and music from the 80s and 90s, and is a reality TV junkie. She drove to Austin from Fresno in a car with three dogs, one cat and two kids. Sweets are her guilty pleasure.

Rayann began life in Indianapolis, but got to Austin as soon as she could. She has 20+ years experience as an interior designer. She also spent more than three years working for a large international construction company on the U.S. Embassy project in Berlin. Beyond that, she’s worked for firms in Tucson, Arizona, Paris, Texas, Waco, Texas, and Austin.

With this varied experience and an apparent lust for adventure, she has moved across two oceans, and loves to travel, quilt and play golf. She is passionate about her family, and particularly partial to ice cream and margaritas. Rayann’s favorite projects are Sun City in Georgetown and Providence Park in Waco. Her favorite books are Pillars of the Earth and Kite Runner; her favorite movie is Gone with the Wind. Musically, you’d find everything from Andrea Boccelli to Alan Jackson to Lady Gaga to Pink on her iPod.

If she weren’t a designer, she believes she’d be doing forensic science. She prides herself on being a self starter, and says she has a high attention to detail with the ability to turn a vision into results.

April grew up on 250 acres in Paris, Tennessee, but settled in Texas six years ago, and considers Austin her home. She is a true Southerner; she enjoys cooking and entertaining, styling interiors, designing jewelry and appreciating the simple things in life. For her, being outdoors, out on the lake, riding her vintage Schwinn bicycles, visiting wineries, listening to live music, playing golf, running and weight training are part of the good life. She also loves football, and playing basketball and tennis. She has also competed in figure bodybuilding competitions.

April is skilled in organizational and strategic planning, new client development, budgeting and project management, and purchasing and merchandising. She excels at developing close relationships with clients and vendors, researching and developing avenues for cost savings, and establishing standards in streamlining processes.

April’s role at studioSIX5 includes generating proposals and contracts for purchasing for senior living communities and generating the utmost in customer service throughout the duration of a project. She is responsible for purchasing consulting and management service agreements, pricing of furnishings, invoicing and managing warranties. She also provides effective outsourcing for new vendor lines, products and furnishings.
